history.Beth Wenger shows how American Jews celebrated civic holidays like Thanksgiving and the Fourth of July in synagogues and Jewish community organizations, and how they sought to commemorate Jewish cultural contributions and patriotism, often tracing their roots to the nation's founding. She looks at Jewish children's literature used to teach lessons about American Jewish heritage and values, which portrayed--and sometimes embellished--the accomplishments of heroic figures in American Jewish history. Wenger also traces how Jews often disagreed about how properly to represent these figures, focusing on the struggle over the legacy of the Jewish Revolutionary hero Haym Salomon.History Lessons demonstrates how American Jews fashioned a collective heritage that fused their Jewish past with their American present and future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh  aAfrican Americans.  aAltman, Addie Richman.  aAmerican Dream.  aAmerican eagle.  aAmericanization Day.  aAmsterdam.  aBialik, Chaim Nahman.  aBildung.  aBill of Rights Day.  aBoston Brahmins.  aCanaan.  aCatholics.  aCold War.  aCommission of Fine Arts.  aConfederate Memorial.  aCosmopolitan (magazine).  aDeclaration of Independence.  aDiaspora.  aEgypt.  aElijah the Prophet.  aEnlightenment.  aFast, Howard.  aFinal Solution.  aFrench Revolution.  aGerman Jews.  aGinsburg, Ruth Bader.  aHadassah.  aHebrew Bible.  aHebrew Sunday school.  aHolocaust.  aIndependence Day.  aJamestown.  aJewish Publication Society.  aKayserling, Meyer.  aKrotoshinsky, Abe.  aKtav Publishing.  aLiessin, Avrohom.  aMarranos.  aMinis family.  aMount Vernon.  aNathans, Benjamin.  aNoah (in Bible).  aOhio State University.  aOppenheim, Samuel.  aPentateuch.  aP